# Security Standards (Healthcare + Flask)

## PII & Health Data
- **Never** log patient names, fiscal codes, diagnoses, or any health-related data
- **Never** expose PII in error messages or API responses beyond what's needed
- Redact sensitive fields before structured logging
- Encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit; key material must stay outside repository

## Authorization
- Every protected endpoint must require auth and scope checks
- Centralize auth/authorization decorators or middleware
- Enforce least privilege when querying tenant/patient scoped data

## Input Validation
- Validate query/path/body payloads explicitly (schema or typed validators)
- Reject unknown fields for sensitive operations
- Different validation rules for create/update where fields differ

## SQL Injection Prevention
- Use parameterized queries/ORM filters only
- Never interpolate user input into SQL strings

## HTTP Security
- Disable debug mode in production
- Add secure headers (`HSTS`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, CSP as applicable)
- Apply CORS with explicit allowlist, never wildcard with credentials
- Webhooks must verify signatures and enforce replay protection if supported

## Dependency Security
- Run vulnerability scan on dependencies before release
- Track and patch vulnerable transitive dependencies quickly

## Secrets
- Secrets only from environment/secret manager
- Never commit `.env`, API keys, service account keys, or tokens
